16: LLVM. By being stubborn about this issue, you are actually harming the copyleft
19: You see, if someone cares about the issue enough, GCC will be forked, a fork that

demonstrate a fork of FSF software is not only possible, but easy to promote with
22: sufficient clout. This is not a good state of affairs for the FSF's definition of
23: FOSS, and is not good for GCC.
25: To put it simply: nothing stops someone from making a GCC fork with the needed

3: push it as the blessed fork if they truly cared.
5: The reason that this hasn't materialised is not because copyleft is magically

10: All this is accomplishing is reducing the effectiveness of GCC as a weapon against
11: non-FOSS software to the point of having the injury potential to non-free software
12: equal to a mosquito. Given enough time, GCC will be doomed to obscurity, at the
13: hands of people with far more clout than the FSF. Clang itself was created under
14: such conditions, and has become dominant in academia and busin
such conditions, and has become dominant in academia and business. This is truly
15: unfortunate, as clang and GCC ought to coexist, for the good of them both --

18: I may not necessarily agree with the ideals of copyleft (I do not feel it is more
19: free than a copycenter license with my definition of free), but I do not want to
20: see GCC doomed to obscurity. I ask you to consider your position carefully, lest
21: your walled copyleft city is simply abandoned.
